{
  "doc_id": "31772",
  "text": "Filamin A interacting protein 1-like (FILIP1L) inhibits the canonical WNT pathway [CITATION_1] . Its inhibition by FILIP1L results in the transcriptional down-regulation of WNT target genes, leading to the inhibition of cell invasion and metastasis [CITATION_2] . We originally observed that FILIP1L was down-regulated through promoter methylation, and its down-regulation induced an invasive phenotype in various types of cancer cells including ovarian [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Modulation of FILIP1L expression in these cancer cells led to the changes in cell invasion [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . We also demonstrated FILIP1L has an anti-angiogenic function that over-expression of FILIP1L in endothelial cells led to decreased cell migration and increased apoptosis, and that tumor vessel-expression of FILIP1L blocked in vivo tumor growth [CITATION_10] . FILIP1L appears to be widely expressed in human tissues and its physiologic function is currently not known. There are five known isoforms of FILIP1L that are generated by alternative splicing; our work focuses on the most prevalent isoform 2 [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] . Its structural homologies and centrosomal localization suggest that FILIP1L may bind elements of the cytoskeleton and chaperone proteins to proteasomes [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] . However, the clinical relevance of FILIP1L down-regulation in cancer progression has yet to be addressed.",
